Spotify Library of Music Analysis¶

Author: Rachel Tong

linkedin.com/in/rachelwtong

This project explores Spotify data from Kaggle which contains data pulled using the Spotify Web API to create an up-to-date and large scale dataset on its library of music. The dataset contains data on artists and tracks and will be used to analyze trends of popular songs over time and create predictive models using machine learning methods. This project is divided into three parts:

  1. Spotify Library of Music Analysis - Exploratory Analysis of the Dataset
  2. Song Recommender - Use of Distance Matrix to Create Recommender System
  3. Popularity Predictor - Machine Learning Models to Predict Song Popularity

The following Kaggle Spotify dataset will be used for this analysis:

  1. tracks 2021.csv (Spotify Web API data pulled in 2021 containing song characteristics and release year)

Specific details about track characteristics can be found here.

1) Analysis of Trends Over Time¶

Songs have generally been getting longer over time with some periods of shorter songs that may correspond with what the characteristics of the popular song genre was at that time. The year with the longest songs on average was 2010, and average song duration has been decreasing since then. This trend correlates with the general decrease in media content duration that has been reported with the advent of short-form media.

avg_yearly_ins = df1.groupby('year',as_index=False)['instrumentalness'].mean().sort_values(by='year')

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
ax.plot(avg_yearly_ins['year'],avg_yearly_ins['instrumentalness'],color="#1DB954")
#ax.set_xticks(filtered_years)
ax.set_title("Song Instrumentalness Over Time")
ax.set_ylabel("Instrumentalness Score")
ax.set_xlabel("Year")
plt.show()

Instrumentalness predicts whether a track contains no vocals. The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content. This makes sense because in recent years, genres that place a trend on instrumentalness--such as jazz and classical--have become increasingly unpopular.¶

Another interesting explanation for this phenomenon is technological innovation in music towards the end of the 1900s. Prior to that time, instruments that were naturally loud (violin, piano, trumpet) were typically used in performances. With new technology such as the pickup, microphone, and portable amp, instruments that were not loud before (acoustic/electric/bass guitar, voice) were able to grow in popularity in large-audience settings. Furthermore, it is much harder to combine traditional stringed instruments with the voice, so the rise in electronic sounds also meant a rise in vocal expression in songs.

Interestingly, the technological innovation music caused a consequent democratization of expression, meaning that artists without any classical technical ability can rise in popularity. Widening the chasm between instrumentalness and popularity is the fact that classical music education is becoming increasingly privatized.

In [22]:
avg_yearly_sp = df1.groupby('year',as_index=True)['speechiness'].mean().sort_index()

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))
ax.plot(avg_yearly_sp,color='#10B954')

ax.set_title("Song Speechiness Over Time")
ax.set_ylabel("Speechiness Score")
ax.set_ylim(0,0.3)
ax.set_xlabel("Year")
plt.show()

Along with the decline in instrumentalness described above, we can see an increase in speechiness, which detects the presence of spoken words in a track. There is a clear spike in speechiness in the 1980s and 1990s.¶

One possible explanation for this spike is the Golden Age of Hip Hop, which took place from the mid 1980s to the mid 1990s, and can be described by greats advances in electronic music technology and rapping technique. During this time, music "witnessed the best recordings form some of the biggest rappers in the genre’s history," and "rhymers like PE’s Chuck D, Big Daddy Kane, KRS-One, Rakim, and LL Cool J basically invented the complex wordplay and lyrical kung-fu of later hip-hop.” Song speechiness before and after this period was more stable, and it's possible that we will continue to see a rise in speechiness along with the decline in instrumentalness as described above.

The liveness of songs decreases slightly as popularity increases. One explanation for this trend could be the fact that higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live. Recording a song in a studio indicates more artist control of the sound, creating a higher quality listening experience for the listener, which would lead studio recorded songs to become more popular than lives ones.¶

Most songs are in between the liveness range of 0.10 and 0.25. The data is very noisy as popularity increases, since the number of songs in the dataset decreases as popularity score increases.

3) Recommending Similar Songs based on Distance Matrix¶

In [38]:
def find_similar_songs(person,song,artist):
    try:
        # making everything lowercase
        song = song.lower()
        artist = artist.lower()
        df1.loc[:,'name'] = df1['name'].str.lower()
        df1.loc[:,'artists'] = df1['artists'].str.lower()
        # if a row in the name column contains the song input string and 
        #    a row in the artist column contains the artist input string,
        #    then select the first name from the dataframe and assign it to the variable correct_song_name
        correct_song_info = df1[(df1['name'].str.contains(song)) & (df1['artists'].str.contains(artist))]
        correct_song_name = correct_song_info['name'].iloc[0]
        print('Hi %s, the song you are looking for is %s by %s' % (person, correct_song_name, correct_song_info['artists'].iloc[0][1:-1]))
 
        # create a song representation of the 10,000 most popular songs based on
        #    5 song characteristics, set index as song name
        songs_rep = df1.sort_values('popularity', ascending=False).loc[df1['popularity']>30].iloc[0:40000].loc[:,['name','danceability','speechiness', 'energy','valence', 'acousticness']].set_index('name')
        
        # create a distance matrix of the songs
        top_songs_dist = pd.DataFrame(distance.cdist(songs_rep,songs_rep),index=songs_rep.index,columns=songs_rep.index)
       
        # create dataframe similar_song from the distance matrix using on the song input
        similar_songs = top_songs_dist[correct_song_name].sort_values().to_frame().reset_index()
        
        similar_songs_pop = similar_songs.merge(df1[['name','popularity','artists']],how='left')
        
        similar_songs_pop = similar_songs_pop.drop_duplicates(subset=['name'])
        similar_songs_pop.set_index('name',inplace=True)                   
        similar_songs_pop.index.rename('Songs similar to %s by %s'% (song.title(), correct_song_info['artists'].iloc[0][1:-1]),inplace=True)
        similar_songs_pop.index=similar_songs_pop.index.str.title()
       
        # renaming columns and fixing capitalization        
        similar_songs_pop.columns = ['Distance score','Popularity','Artists']
        similar_songs_pop.loc[:,'Artists'] = similar_songs_pop['Artists'].str.title()
        
        
        # return the top 10 most similar songs out of the 10,000 most popular songs
        print("Here are 10 songs you might like!")
        return similar_songs_pop.iloc[1:10]
    except:
        print('Sorry, song not available')

person = str(input("Enter your name: "))
song_input = str(input("Song: "))
artist_input = str(input("Artist: "))
find_similar_songs(person,song_input,artist_input)

a) Linear Regression¶

In [34]:
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7,4))

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split
(df_char[["explicit",'loudness','energy','acousticness']],df_char['popularity'],train_size=.95)

model = lr().fit(X=X_train, y=y_train)

y_hat = model.predict(X_test)

plt.scatter(y_hat, y_test,alpha=0.1,color='#142424') # plotting the predicted value on the x axis, actual value on the y axis
ax.set_xlabel('Predicted popularity')
ax.set_ylabel('Actual popularity from y_test')
ax.set_title("Predicted vs. actual song popularity",size=14)
plt.show()

Because this model was trained on all the data (not just one year), we can see that there is little correlation between the most correlated features found above and popularity across all years. This model is not a good predictor of song popularity.

This makes sense because the track feature of popularity is calculated by the Spotify algorithm and is based, in the most part, on the total number of plays the track has had and how recent those plays are. Because the popularity score is high for recent songs with a lot of plays, but lower for older songs that might've been very popular at the time, it is not a good idea to aggregate the data over many years to try to predict the popularity score, which is an indicator of current-day popularity.

Thus, going forward we will predict popularity based on song characteristics for 2020.

N.B: we are testing on only 5% of the data due to the large size of the dataset (~500k tracks).

From evaluating root mean squared error, we can see that the decision tree regressior is the best model to predict song popularity based on song characteristics for 2020. Some features had little to no impact on popularity, which likely caused the high RMSE of the random forest regressor. Finally, the decision tree regressor uses the most predictive features to forecast popularity, allowing it to have the lowest RMSE out of all the models investigated.
